# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: construction-bim
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The concept of BIM has been in development since the 1970s, but it only became an agreed term in the early 2000s.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The development of standards and the adoption of BIM has progressed at different speeds in different countries.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The first software tools developed for modeling buildings emerged in the late 1970s and early 1980s, and included workstation products such as Chuck Eastman's Building Description System and GLIDE, RUCAPS, Sonata, Reflex and Gable 4D Series.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The early applications, and the hardware needed to run them, were expensive, which limited widespread adoption.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The pioneering role of applications such as RUCAPS, Sonata and Reflex has been recognized by Laiserin as well as the UK's Royal Academy of Engineering; former GMW employee Jonathan Ingram worked on all three products.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] What became known as BIM products differed from architectural drafting tools such as AutoCAD by allowing the addition of further information (time, cost, manufacturers' details, sustainability, and maintenance information, etc.) to the building model.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] However, Graphisoft founder Gábor Bojár has acknowledged to Jonathan Ingram in an open letter, that Sonata "was more advanced in 1986 than ArchiCAD at that time", adding that it "surpassed already the matured definition of 'BIM' specified only about one and a half decade later".
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The term 'Building Information Model' first appeared in a 1992 paper by G.A. van Nederveen and F.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] However, the terms 'Building Information Model' and 'Building Information Modeling' (including the acronym "BIM") did not become popularly used until some 10 years later.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Facilitating exchange and interoperability of information in digital format was variously with differing terminology: by Graphisoft as "Virtual Building" or "Single Building Model", Bentley Systems as "Integrated Project Models", and by Autodesk or Vectorworks as "Building Information Modeling".
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In 2002, Autodesk released a white paper entitled "Building Information Modeling," and other software vendors also started to assert their involvement in the field.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] By hosting contributions from Autodesk, Bentley Systems and Graphisoft, plus other industry observers, in 2003, Jerry Laiserin helped popularize and standardize the term as a common name for the digital representation of the building process.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] As some BIM software developers have created proprietary data structures in their software, data and files created by one vendor's applications may not work in other vendor solutions.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] To achieve interoperability between applications, neutral, non-proprietary or open standards for sharing BIM data among different software applications have been developed.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Poor software interoperability has long been regarded as an obstacle to industry efficiency in general and to BIM adoption in particular.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] An early BIM standard was the CIMSteel Integration Standard, CIS/2, a product model and data exchange file format for structural steel project information (CIMsteel: Computer Integrated Manufacturing of Constructional Steelwork).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] CIS/2 enables seamless and integrated information exchange during the design and construction of steel framed structures.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] It was developed by the University of Leeds and the UK's Steel Construction Institute in the late 1990s, with inputs from Georgia Tech, and was approved by the American Institute of Steel Construction as its data exchange format for structural steel in 2000.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM is often associated with Industry Foundation Classes (IFCs) and aecXML – data structures for representing information – developed by buildingSMART.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] IFC is recognised by the ISO and has been an international standard, ISO 16739, since 2013.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] OpenBIM is an initiative by buildingSMART that promotes open standards and interoperability.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Based on the IFC standard, it allows vendor-neutral BIM data exchange.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] OpenBIM standards also include BIM Collaboration Format (BCF) for issue tracking and Information Delivery Specification (IDS) for defining model requirements.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Construction Operations Building information exchange (COBie) is also associated with BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] COBie was devised by Bill East of the United States Army Corps of Engineers in 2007, and helps capture and record equipment lists, product data sheets, warranties, spare parts lists, and preventive maintenance schedules.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] This information is used to support operations, maintenance and asset management once a built asset is in service.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In December 2011, it was approved by the US-based National Institute of Building Sciences as part of its National Building Information Model (NBIMS-US) standard.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] COBie has been incorporated into software, and may take several forms including spreadsheet, IFC, and ifcXML.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In early 2013 BuildingSMART was working on a lightweight XML format, COBieLite, which became available for review in April 2013.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In September 2014, a code of practice regarding COBie was issued as a British Standard: BS 1192-4.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In January 2019, ISO published the first two parts of ISO 19650, providing a framework for building information modelling, based on process standards developed in the United Kingdom.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] UK BS and PAS 1192 specifications formed the basis of further parts of the ISO 19650 series, with Part 3 (asset management) and Part 5 (security management) published in 2020; Part 4 (information exchange) followed in 2022 and Part 6 (health and safety) in 2025.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Parts 1-3 were subject to review from 2024, and proposed amendments (a Draft Information Standard, DIS) for parts 1 and 2 were published in early March 2026, with amendments for part 3 following in June 2026.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The IEC/ISO 81346 series for reference designation has published 81346-12:2018, also known as RDS-CW (Reference Designation System for Construction Works).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The use of RDS-CW offers the prospect of integrating BIM with complementary international standards based classification systems being developed for the Power Plant sector.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] use of a shared digital representation of a built asset ... to facilitate design, construction and operation processes to form a reliable basis for decisions.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Building Information Modeling (BIM) is a digital representation of physical and functional characteristics of a facility.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] A BIM is a shared knowledge resource for information about a facility forming a reliable basis for decisions during its life-cycle; defined as existing from earliest conception to demolition.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Traditional building design was largely reliant upon two-dimensional technical drawings (plans, elevations, sections, etc.).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Building information modeling extends the three primary spatial dimensions (width, height and depth), incorporating information about time (so-called 4D BIM), cost (5D BIM), asset management, sustainability, etc.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM therefore covers more than just geometry.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM authoring tools present a design as combinations of "objects" – vague and undefined, generic or product-specific, solid shapes or void-space oriented (like the shape of a room), that carry their geometry, relations, and attributes.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM applications allow extraction of different views from a building model for drawing production and other uses.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] These different views are automatically consistent, being based on a single definition of each object instance.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM software also defines objects parametrically; that is, the objects are defined as parameters and relations to other objects so that if a related object is amended, dependent ones will automatically also change.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Each model element can carry attributes for selecting and ordering them automatically, providing cost estimates as well as material tracking and ordering.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] For the professionals involved in a project, BIM enables a virtual information model to be shared by the design team (architects, landscape architects, surveyors, civil, structural and building services engineers, etc.), the main contractor and subcontractors, and the owner/operator.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Each professional adds discipline-specific data to the shared model – commonly, a 'federated' model which combines several different disciplines' models into one.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Combining models enables visualisation of all models in a single environment, better coordination and development of designs, enhanced clash avoidance and detection, and improved time and cost decision-making.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] "BIM wash" or "BIM washing" is a term sometimes used to describe inflated, and/or deceptive, claims of using or delivering BIM services or products.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Use of BIM goes beyond the planning and design phase of a project, extending throughout the life cycle of the asset.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The supporting processes of building lifecycle management include cost management, construction management, project management, facility operation and application in green building.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Agreed source of information for any given project or asset, for collecting, managing and disseminating each information container through a managed process.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] A CDE workflow describes the processes to be used while a CDE solution can provide the underlying technologies.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] A CDE is used to share data across a project or asset lifecycle, supporting collaboration across a whole project team.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The concept of a CDE overlaps with enterprise content management, ECM, but with a greater focus on BIM issues.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Building information models span the whole concept-to-occupation time-span.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] To ensure efficient management of information processes throughout this span, a BIM manager might be appointed.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIMs were also developed to different levels of development (LOD) (sometimes also called levels of detail) reflecting the relevant levels of detailing needed from early to later stages of a project.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The 2018 publication of ISO 19650-1 then introduced the concept of Level of Information Need (LOIN), standardised in 2024 in ISO 7817-1:2024.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Participants in the building process are constantly challenged to deliver successful projects despite tight budgets, limited staffing, accelerated schedules, and limited or conflicting information.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The significant disciplines such as architectural, structural and MEP designs should be well-coordinated, as two things can't take place at the same place and time.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM additionally is able to aid in collision detection, identifying the exact location of discrepancies.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The BIM concept envisages virtual construction of a facility prior to its actual physical construction, in order to reduce uncertainty, improve safety, work out problems, and simulate and analyze potential impacts.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Sub-contractors from every trade can input critical information into the model before beginning construction, with opportunities to pre-fabricate or pre-assemble some systems off-site.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Waste can be minimised on-site and products delivered on a just-in-time basis rather than being stock-piled on-site.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Quantities and shared properties of materials can be extracted easily.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Scopes of work can be isolated and defined.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Systems, assemblies and sequences can be shown in a relative scale with the entire facility or group of facilities.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM also prevents errors by enabling conflict or 'clash detection' whereby the computer model visually highlights to the team where parts of the building (e.g.:structural frame and building services pipes or ducts) may wrongly intersect.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM can bridge the information loss associated with handing a project from design team, to construction team and to building owner/operator, by allowing each group to add to and reference back to all information they acquire during their period of contribution to the BIM model.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Enabling an effective handover of information from design and construction (including via IFC or COBie) can thus yield benefits to the facility owner or operator.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM-related processes relating to longer-term asset management are also covered in ISO-19650 Part 3.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] For example, a building owner may find evidence of a water leak in a building.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Rather than exploring the physical building, the owner may turn to the model and see that a water valve is located in the suspect location.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The owner could also have in the model the specific valve size, manufacturer, part number, and any other information ever researched in the past, pending adequate computing power.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Such problems were initially addressed by Leite and Akinci when developing a vulnerability representation of facility contents and threats for supporting the identification of vulnerabilities in building emergencies.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Dynamic information about the building, such as sensor measurements and control signals from the building systems, can also be incorporated within software to support analysis of building operation and maintenance.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] There have been attempts at creating information models for older, pre-existing facilities.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Trying to retrospectively model a building constructed in, say 1927, requires numerous assumptions about design standards, building codes, construction methods, materials, etc, and is, therefore, more complex than building a model during design.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM in green building, or "green BIM", is a process that can help architecture, engineering and construction firms to improve sustainability in the built environment.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] It can allow architects and engineers to integrate and analyze environmental issues in their design over the life cycle of the asset.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In the ERANet projects EPC4SES and FinSESCo projects worked on the digital representation of the energy demand of the building.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The nucleus is the XML from issuing Energy Performance Certificates, amended by roof data to be able to retrieve the position and size of PV or PV/T.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] China began its exploration on informatisation in 2001.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The Ministry of Construction announced BIM was the key application technology of informatisation in *"Ten new technologies of construction industry"* (by 2010).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The Ministry of Science and Technology (MOST) clearly announced BIM technology as a national key research and application project in *"12th Five-Year" Science and Technology Development Planning.* Therefore, the year 2011 was described as *"The First Year of China's BIM"*.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In 2006 the Hong Kong Housing Authority introduced BIM, and then set a target of full BIM implementation in 2014/2015.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BuildingSmart Hong Kong was inaugurated in Hong Kong SAR in late April 2012.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The Government of Hong Kong mandates the use of BIM for all government projects over HK$30M since 1 January 2018.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] India Building Information Modelling Association (IBIMA) is a national-level society that represents the entire Indian BIM community.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In India BIM is also known as VDC: **V**irtual **D**esign and **C**onstruction.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Due to its population and economic growth, India has an expanding construction market.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In spite of this, BIM usage was reported by only 22% of respondents in a 2014 survey.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In 2019, government officials said BIM could help save up to 20% by shortening construction time, and urged wider adoption by infrastructure ministries.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The Iran Building Information Modeling Association (IBIMA) was founded in 2012 by professional engineers from five universities in Iran, including the Civil and Environmental Engineering Department at Amirkabir University of Technology.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] While it is not currently active, IBIMA aims to share knowledge resources to support construction engineering management decision-making.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM implementation is targeted towards BIM Stage 2 by the year 2020 led by the Construction Industry Development Board (CIDB Malaysia).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Under the Construction Industry Transformation Plan (CITP 2016–2020), it is hoped more emphasis on technology adoption across the project life-cycle will induce higher productivity.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The Building and Construction Authority (BCA) has announced that BIM would be introduced for architectural submission (by 2013), structural and M&E submissions (by 2014) and eventually for plan submissions of all projects with gross floor area of more than 5,000 square meters by 2015.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The BCA Academy is training students in BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport (MLIT) has announced "Start of BIM pilot project in government building and repairs" (by 2010).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Japan Institute of Architects (JIA) released the BIM guidelines (by 2012), which showed the agenda and expected effect of BIM to architects.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] MLIT announced " BIM will be mandated for all of its public works from the fiscal year of 2023, except those having particular reasons".
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The works subject to WTO Government Procurement Agreement shall comply with the published ISO standards related to BIM such as ISO19650 series as determined by the Article 10 (Technical Specification) of the Agreement.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Small BIM-related seminars and independent BIM effort existed in South Korea even in the 1990s.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] However, it was not until the late 2000s that the Korean industry paid attention to BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The first industry-level BIM conference was held in April 2008, after which, BIM has been spread very rapidly.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Since 2010, the Korean government has been gradually increasing the scope of BIM-mandated projects.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] McGraw Hill published a detailed report in 2012 on the status of BIM adoption and implementation in South Korea.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Dubai Municipality issued a circular (196) in 2014 mandating BIM use for buildings of a certain size, height or type.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The one page circular initiated strong interest in BIM and the market responded in preparation for more guidelines and direction.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In 2015 the Municipality issued another circular (207) titled 'Regarding the expansion of applying the (BIM) on buildings and facilities in the emirate of Dubai' which made BIM mandatory on more projects by reducing the minimum size and height requirement for projects requiring BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] This second circular drove BIM adoption further with several projects and organizations adopting UK BIM standards as best practice.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In 2016, the UAE's Quality and Conformity Commission set up a BIM steering group to investigate statewide adoption of BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Austrian standards for digital modeling are summarized in the ÖNORM A 6241, published on 15 March 2015.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The ÖNORM A 6241-1 (BIM Level 2), which replaced the ÖNORM A 6240-4, has been extended in the detailed and executive design stages, and corrected in the lack of definitions.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The ÖNORM A 6241-2 (BIM Level 3) includes all the requirements for the BIM Level 3 (iBIM).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The Czech BIM Council, established in May 2011, aims to implement BIM methodologies into the Czech building and designing processes, education, standards and legislation.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In Estonia digital construction cluster (Digitaalehituse Klaster) was formed in 2015 to develop BIM solutions for the whole life-cycle of construction.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The strategic objective of the cluster is to develop an innovative digital construction environment as well as VDC new product development, Grid and e-construction portal to increase the international competitiveness and sales of Estonian businesses in the construction field.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The cluster is equally co-funded by European Structural and Investment Funds through Enterprise Estonia and by the members of the cluster with a total budget of 600 000 euros for the period 2016–2018.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The French arm of buildingSMART, called Mediaconstruct (existing since 1989), is supporting digital transformation in France.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] A building transition digital plan – French acronym PTNB – was created in 2013 (mandated since 2015 to 2017 and under several ministries).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] A 2013 survey of European BIM practice showed France in last place, but, with government support, in 2017 it had risen to third place with more than 30% of real estate projects carried out using BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In December 2015, the German minister for transport Alexander Dobrindt announced a timetable for the introduction of mandatory BIM for German road and rail projects from the end of 2020.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Speaking in April 2016, he said digital design and construction must become standard for construction projects in Germany, with Germany two to three years behind The Netherlands and the UK in aspects of implementing BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM was piloted in many areas of German infrastructure delivery and in July 2022 Volker Wissing, Federal Minister for Digital and Transport, announced that, from 2025, BIM will be used as standard in the construction of federal trunk roads in addition to the rail sector.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In November 2017, Ireland's Department for Public Expenditure and Reform launched a strategy to increase use of digital technology in delivery of key public works projects, requiring the use of BIM to be phased in over the next four years.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] 50, in April 2016 Italy has included into its own legislation several European directives including 2014/24/EU on Public Procurement.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The decree states among the main goals of public procurement the "rationalization of designing activities and of all connected verification processes, through the progressive adoption of digital methods and electronic instruments such as Building and Infrastructure Information Modelling".
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] A norm in 8 parts is also being written to support the transition: UNI 11337-1, UNI 11337-4 and UNI 11337-5 were published in January 2017, with five further chapters to follow within a year.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In early 2018 the Italian Ministry of Infrastructure and Transport issued a decree (DM 01/12/17) creating a governmental BIM Mandate compelling public client organisations to adopt a digital approach by 2025, with an incremental obligation which will start on 1 January 2019.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Lithuania is moving towards adoption of BIM infrastructure by founding a public body "Skaitmeninė statyba" (Digital Construction), which is managed by 13 associations.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Also, there is a BIM work group established by Lietuvos Architektų Sąjunga (a Lithuanian architects body).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The initiative intends Lithuania to adopt BIM, Industry Foundation Classes (IFC) and National Construction Classification as standard.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] An international conference "Skaitmeninė statyba Lietuvoje" (Digital Construction in Lithuania) has been held annually since 2012.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] On 1 November 2011, the Rijksgebouwendienst, the agency within the Dutch Ministry of Housing, Spatial Planning and the Environment that manages government buildings, introduced the Rgd BIM Standard, which it updated on 1 July 2012.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In Norway BIM has been used increasingly since 2008.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Several large public clients require use of BIM in open formats (IFC) in most or all of their projects.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The Government Building Authority bases its processes on BIM in open formats to increase process speed and quality, and all large and several small and medium-sized contractors use BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] National BIM development is centred around the local organisation, buildingSMART Norway which represents 25% of the Norwegian construction industry.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIMKlaster (BIM Cluster) is a non-governmental, non-profit organisation established in 2012 with the aim of promoting BIM development in Poland.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In September 2016, the Ministry of Infrastructure and Construction began a series of expert meetings concerning the application of BIM methodologies in the construction industry.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The Russian government has approved a list of the regulations that provide the creation of a legal framework for the use of information modeling of buildings in construction and encourages the use of BIM in government projects.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The BIM Association of Slovakia, "BIMaS", was established in January 2013 as the first Slovak professional organisation focused on BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Although there are neither standards nor legislative requirements to deliver projects in BIM, many architects, structural engineers and contractors, plus a few investors are already applying BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] A Slovak implementation strategy created by BIMaS and supported by the Chamber of Civil Engineers and Chamber of Architects has yet to be approved by Slovak authorities due to their low interest in such innovation.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] A July 2015 meeting at Spain's Ministry of Infrastructure [Ministerio de Fomento] launched the country's national BIM strategy, making BIM a mandatory requirement on public sector projects with a possible starting date of 2018.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Following a February 2015 BIM summit in Barcelona, professionals in Spain established a BIM commission (ITeC) to drive the adoption of BIM in Catalonia.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Since 2009 through the initiative of buildingSmart Switzerland, then 2013, BIM awareness among a broader community of engineers and architects was raised due to the open competition for Basel's Felix Platter Hospital where a BIM coordinator was sought.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM has also been a subject of events by the Swiss Society for Engineers and Architects, SIA.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In May 2011 UK Government Chief Construction Adviser Paul Morrell called for BIM adoption on UK government construction projects.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Morrell also told construction professionals to adopt BIM or be "Betamaxed out".
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In June 2011 the UK government published its BIM strategy, announcing its intention to require collaborative 3D BIM (with all project and asset information, documentation and data being electronic) on its projects by 2016.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Initially, compliance would require building data to be delivered in a vendor-neutral 'COBie' format, thus overcoming the limited interoperability of BIM software suites available on the market.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The UK Government BIM Task Group led the government's BIM programme and requirements, including a free-to-use set of UK standards and tools that defined 'level 2 BIM'.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In April 2016, the UK Government published a new central web portal as a point of reference for the industry for 'level 2 BIM'.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The work of the BIM Task Group then continued under the stewardship of the Cambridge-based Centre for Digital Built Britain (CDBB), announced in December 2017 and formally launched in early 2018.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In November 2017, the UK BIM Alliance merged with the UK and Ireland chapter of BuildingSMART.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In October 2019, CDBB, the UK BIM Alliance (since October 2022, known as 'nima') and the BSI Group launched the UK BIM Framework.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Superseding the BIM levels approach, the framework describes an overarching approach to implementing BIM in the UK, giving free guidance on integrating the international ISO 19650 series of standards into UK processes and practice.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] National Building Specification (NBS) has published research into BIM adoption in the UK since 2011, and in 2020 published its 10th annual BIM report.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In 2011, 43% of respondents had not heard of BIM; in 2020 73% said they were using BIM.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Several organizations support BIM adoption and implementation in Canada: the Canada BIM Council (CANBIM, founded in 2008), the Institute for BIM in Canada, and buildingSMART Canada (the Canadian chapter of buildingSMART International).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Public Services and Procurement Canada (formerly Public Works and Government Services Canada) is committed to using non-proprietary or "OpenBIM" BIM standards and avoids specifying any specific proprietary BIM format.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Designers are required to use the international standards of interoperability for BIM (IFC).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] an object-oriented building development tool that utilizes 5-D modeling concepts, information technology and software interoperability to design, construct and operate a building project, as well as communicate its details.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Although the concept of BIM and relevant processes are being explored by contractors, architects and developers alike, the term itself has been questioned and debated with alternatives including Virtual Building Environment (VBE) also considered.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Unlike some countries such as the UK, the US has not adopted a set of national BIM guidelines, allowing different systems to remain in competition.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In 2021, the National Institute of Building Sciences (NIBS) looked at applying UK BIM experiences to developing shared US BIM standards and processes.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The US National BIM Standard had largely been developed through volunteer efforts; NIBS aimed to create a national BIM programme to drive effective adoption at a national scale.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM is seen to be closely related to Integrated Project Delivery (IPD) where the primary motive is to bring the teams together early on in the project.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] A full implementation of BIM also requires the project teams to collaborate from the inception stage and formulate model sharing and ownership contract documents.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The American Institute of Architects has defined BIM as "a model-based technology linked with a database of project information", and this reflects the general reliance on database technology as the foundation.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In the future, structured text documents such as specifications may be able to be searched and linked to regional, national, and international standards.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM has the potential to play a vital role in the Nigerian AEC sector.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In addition to its potential clarity and transparency, it may help promote standardization across the industry.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Similarly, an assessment of the current 'state of the art' by Kori found that medium and large firms were leading the adoption of BIM in the industry.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Smaller firms were less advanced with respect to process and policy adherence.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] There has been little adoption of BIM in the built environment due to construction industry resistance to changes or new ways of doing things.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The industry is still working with conventional 2D CAD systems in services and structural designs, although production could be in 3D systems.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] There is virtually no utilisation of 4D and 5D systems.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] BIM Africa Initiative, primarily based in Nigeria, is a non-profit institute advocating the adoption of BIM across Africa.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Since 2018, it has been engaging with professionals and the government towards the digital transformation of the built industry.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Produced annually by its research and development committee, the African BIM Report gives an overview of BIM adoption across the African continent.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The South African BIM Institute, established in May 2015, aims to enable technical experts to discuss digital construction solutions that can be adopted by professionals working within the construction sector.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Its initial task was to promote the SA BIM Protocol.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] There are no mandated or national best practice BIM standards or protocols in South Africa.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Organisations implement company-specific BIM standards and protocols at best (there are isolated examples of cross-industry alliances).
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In February 2016, Infrastructure Australia recommended: "Governments should make the use of Building Information Modelling (BIM) mandatory for the design of large-scale complex infrastructure projects.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In support of a mandatory rollout, the Australian Government should commission the Australasian Procurement and Construction Council, working with industry, to develop appropriate guidance around the adoption and use of BIM; and common standards and protocols to be applied when using BIM".
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In 2015, many projects in the rebuilding of Christchurch were being assembled in detail on a computer using BIM well before workers set foot on the site.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The New Zealand government started a BIM acceleration committee, as part of a productivity partnership with the goal of 20 per cent more efficiency in the construction industry by 2020.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Today, BIM use is still not mandated in the country while several challenges have been identified for its implementation in the country.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] However, members of the AEC industry and academia have developed a national BIM handbook providing definitions, case studies and templates.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Some purposes or uses of BIM may be described as 'dimensions'.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] However, there is little consensus on definitions beyond 5D.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] 4D modelling enables project participants (architects, designers, contractors, clients) to plan, sequence the physical activities, visualise the critical path of a series of events, mitigate the risks, report and monitor progress of activities through the lifetime of the project.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] 4D BIM enables a sequence of events to be depicted visually on a time line that has been populated by a 3D model, augmenting traditional Gantt charts and critical path (CPM) schedules often used in project management.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] Construction sequences can be reviewed as a series of problems using 4D BIM, enabling users to explore options, manage solutions and optimize results.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] As an advanced construction management technique, it has been used by project delivery teams working on larger projects.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] 4D BIM has traditionally been used for higher end projects due to the associated costs, but technologies are now emerging that allow the process to be used by laymen or to drive processes such as manufacture.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In June 2016, McKinsey & Company identified 5D BIM technology as one of five big ideas poised to disrupt construction.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] It defined 5D BIM as "a five-dimensional representation of the physical and functional characteristics of any project.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] In the project life cycle context, a 6D model is usually delivered to the owner when a construction project is finished.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The "As-Built" BIM model is populated with relevant building component information such as product data and details, maintenance/operation manuals, cut sheet specifications, photos, warranty data, web links to product online sources, manufacturer information and contacts, etc.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] This database is made accessible to the users/owners through a customized proprietary web-based environment.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] This is intended to aid facilities managers in the operation and maintenance of the facility.
[src:construction-bim/4d-bim] The term is less commonly used in the UK and has been replaced with reference to the Asset Information Requirements (AIR) and an Asset Information Model (AIM) as specified in BS EN ISO 19650-3:2020.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The company was renamed **Revit Technology Corporation** in January 2000.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Autodesk, best known for its AutoCAD line of products, purchased Revit Technology Corporation for US $133 million in 2002.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The purchase allowed more research, development and improvement of the software.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Autodesk, through its Revit platform, operates in the BIM market alongside Tekla Structures, Trimble, Bentley Systems and the Nemetschek group.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The Nemetschek group includes Graphisoft's ArchiCAD, as well as Allplan and Vectorworks.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] At the time, several other software packages—such as ArchiCAD and Reflex—provided a three-dimensional virtual building model and let the user control individual components via parameters (parametric components).
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Two key differences in Revit were that users created parametric components in a graphical "family editor" rather than a programming language.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The model captured relationships between components, views, and annotations, allowing any change to automatically propagate to keep the model consistent.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] For example, moving a wall updated neighboring walls, floors and roofs, corrected the placement and values of dimensions and notes, adjusted the floor areas reported in schedules, redrew section views, etc.—so that the model remained connected and all documentation was coordinated.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The concept of bi-directional associativity between components, views and annotations was a distinguishing feature of Revit for many releases.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The ease of making changes inspired the name Revit, a contraction of *Revise-Instantly*.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] At the heart of Revit is a parametric change propagation engine that relied on a new technology, context-driven parametrics, that was more scalable than the variational and history-driven parametrics used in mechanical CAD software.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The term *parametric building model* was adopted to reflect the fact that changes to parameters drove the whole building model and associated documentation, not just individual components.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Revit version 1.0 was released on April 5, 2000.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The software progressed rapidly, with version 2.0, 3.0, 3.1, 4.0 and 4.1 released in August 2000; October 2000; February 2001; June 2001; November 2001; and January 2002, respectively.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The software was initially offered only as a monthly rental, with no option to purchase.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Licensing was controlled by an entirely automatic process, an innovation at a time when human intervention and manual transmission of authorization codes was required to buy other types of design software.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Autodesk released several versions of Revit after 2004.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] In 2005 Revit Structure was introduced, then in 2006 Revit MEP.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] After the 2006 release *Revit Building* was renamed Revit Architecture.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] In 2011 Dynamo was released in beta form allowing first glimpses of directly programming the behavior of hosted components through a drag and drop node interface.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] This is similar to the way the visual programming language Grasshopper 3d works on objects in Rhinoceros 3D.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] In 2012 Revit LT became the newest version of Revit on the market.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] It was a feature limited or Lite version of Revit which excluded features such as rendering and multi-user environments.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] In 2013, Autodesk began introducing rental licensing for some of its products, including Revit.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Since Revit 2013 the different disciplines have been rolled into one product, simply called Revit.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Autodesk sells several packages or 'industry collections'; Revit is included in the *AEC Collection*.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Revit is available in multiple language localizations: English, German, French, Spanish, Portuguese, Italian, Russian, Polish, Czech, Chinese, Japanese and Korean.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] With the release of Revit 2016, Autodesk dropped support for 32-bit Windows.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The Revit work environment allows users to manipulate whole buildings or assemblies (in the project environment) or individual 3D shapes (in the family editor environment).
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Modeling tools can be used with pre-made solid objects or imported geometric models.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] However, Revit is not a NURBS modeller and also lacks the ability to manipulate an object's individual polygons except on some specific object types such as roofs, slabs and terrain or in the massing environment.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Revit includes categories of objects ("families" in Revit terminology).
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] An experienced user can create realistic and accurate families ranging from furniture to lighting fixtures, as well as import existing models from other programs.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Revit families can be created as parametric models with dimensions and properties.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] This lets users modify a given component by changing predefined parameters such as *height*, *width* or *number* in the case of an array.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] In this way a *family* defines a geometry that is controlled by parameters, each combination of parameters can be saved as a *type*, and each occurrence (instance in Revit) of a *type* can also contain further variations.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] For example, a swing door may be a Family.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] It may have types that describe different sizes and the actual building model has instances of those types placed in walls where instance-based parameters could specify the door hardware uniquely for each occurrence of the door.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Although Revit software comes with a range of families out of the box (OOTB), they are limited, so users may find a need to build their own families or buy them from online stores.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Because of copyright issues in project work, fully 3D-modeled Revit project models are rarely for sale.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Indeed, as most projects are site-specific and bespoke, the demand for existing models is light anyway.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] However, new practices or students of Revit may want to refer to completed models.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] There are a few sources for these, including websites such as BIMGallery and GrabCad.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Since version 3.0 Revit enables multiple users to work on the same building model.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The workflow is similar to the use of a version control system in software engineering, that allows multiple developers to reliably collaborate on a common code base.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Each Revit user works on a local copy of the design, periodically checking in the work into the central repository.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] New user starts with creating a local copy of this repository.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] When a user starts modifying some building elements, these elements get automatically locked, preventing others from modifying them.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The locks are maintained in the central repository.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The elements stay locked until the "borrower" checks in her work and releases the locks.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Patented technology called "worksharing" allows Revit to minimize the set of elements being locked while allowing change propagation engine to update as many elements as needed, including the elements that are not locked.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Revit typically avoids merge conflicts during check-in.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] In early Revit versions the central repository has been a folder on LAN.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] This option is still available and appropriate for co-located design team.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Since 2013 Autodesk also offers hosted cloud-based central repositories for Revit as a service.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] When a user creates a building, model or any other kind of object in Revit, they may use Revit's rendering engine to make a more realistic image of what is otherwise a very diagrammatic model.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The user accomplishes this either by using the premade model, wall, floor, etc., tools, or making their own models, walls, materials, etc.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Since Revit's 2010 release, the software came with a plethora of predefined materials, each of which can be modified to the user's desires.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] The user can also begin with a "Generic" material.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Cloud-based rendering with the experimental plug-in dubbed Project Neon, located on Autodesk Labs is in the beta phases and allows for the user to render their images through their Autodesk account instead of locally through their own computers.
[src:construction-bim/autodesk-revit] Revit models may also be linked directly into Autodesk 3ds Max (release 2013 and later) for more advanced rendering and animation projects with much of their material and object information maintained.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Its use in designing electronic systems is known as *electronic design automation* (*EDA*).
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] In mechanical design it is known as *mechanical design automation* (*MDA*), which includes the process of creating a technical drawing with the use of computer software.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD software for mechanical design uses either vector-based graphics to depict the objects of traditional drafting, or may also produce raster graphics showing the overall appearance of designed objects.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] However, it involves more than just shapes.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] As in the manual drafting of technical and engineering drawings, the output of CAD must convey information, such as materials, processes, dimensions, and tolerances, according to application-specific conventions.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD may be used to design curves and figures in two-dimensional (2D) space; or curves, surfaces, and solids in three-dimensional (3D) space.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD is an important industrial art extensively used in many applications, including automotive, shipbuilding, and aerospace industries, industrial and architectural design (building information modeling), prosthetics, and many more.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD is also widely used to produce computer animation for special effects in movies, advertising and technical manuals, often called DCC digital content creation.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] The modern ubiquity and power of computers means that even perfume bottles and shampoo dispensers are designed using techniques unheard of by engineers of the 1960s.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Because of its enormous economic importance, CAD has been a major driving force for research in computational geometry, computer graphics (both hardware and software), and discrete differential geometry.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] The design of geometric models for object shapes, in particular, is occasionally called **computer-aided geometric design** (**CAGD**).
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Computer-aided design is one of the many tools used by engineers and designers and is used in many ways depending on the profession of the user and the type of software in question.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Potential blockage of view corridors and shadow studies are also frequently analyzed through the use of CAD.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] There are several different types of CAD, each requiring the operator to think differently about how to use them and design their virtual components in a different manner.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Virtually all of CAD tools rely on constraint concepts that are used to define geometric or non-geometric elements of a model.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] There are many producers of the lower-end 2D sketching systems, including a number of free and open-source programs.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] These provide an approach to the drawing process where scale and placement on the drawing sheet can easily be adjusted in the final draft as required, unlike in hand drafting.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Top-end CAD systems offer the capability to incorporate more organic, aesthetic and ergonomic features into the designs.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Freeform surface modeling is often combined with solids to allow the designer to create products that fit the human form and visual requirements as well as they interface with the machine.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Today, CAD systems exist for all the major platforms (Windows, Linux, UNIX and Mac OS X); some packages support multiple platforms.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Starting with the IBM Drafting System in the mid-1960s, computer-aided design systems began to provide more capabilities than just an ability to reproduce manual drafting with electronic drafting, and the cost-benefit for companies to switch to CAD became apparent.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] The software automated many tasks that are taken for granted from computer systems today, such as automated generation of bills of materials, auto layout in integrated circuits, interference checking, and many others.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Eventually, CAD provided the designer with the ability to perform engineering calculations.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] During this transition, calculations were still performed either by hand or by those individuals who could run computer programs.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD was a revolutionary change in the engineering industry, where draftsman, designer, and engineer roles that had previously been separate began to merge.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD is an example of the pervasive effect computers were beginning to have on the industry.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Current computer-aided design software packages range from 2D vector-based drafting systems to 3D solid and surface modelers.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Modern CAD packages can also frequently allow rotations in three dimensions, allowing viewing of a designed object from any desired angle, even from the inside looking out.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Some CAD software is capable of dynamic mathematical modeling.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD technology is used in the design of tools and machinery and in the drafting and design of all types of buildings, from small residential types (houses) to the largest commercial and industrial structures (hospitals and factories).
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD is mainly used for detailed design of 3D models or 2D drawings of physical components, but it is also used throughout the engineering process from conceptual design and layout of products, through strength and dynamic analysis of assemblies to definition of manufacturing methods of components.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] It can also be used to design objects such as jewelry, furniture, appliances, etc.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Furthermore, many CAD applications now offer advanced rendering and animation capabilities so engineers can better visualize their product designs.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] 4D BIM is a type of virtual construction engineering simulation incorporating time or schedule-related information for project management.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD has become an especially important technology within the scope of computer-aided technologies, with benefits such as lower product development costs and a greatly shortened design cycle.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD enables designers to layout and develop work on screen, print it out and save it for future editing, saving time on their drawings.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] In the 2000s, some CAD system software vendors shipped their distributions with a dedicated license manager software that controlled how often or how many users can utilize the CAD system.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] It could run either on a local machine (by loading from a local storage device) or a local network fileserver and was usually tied to a specific IP address in latter case.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] CAD software enables engineers and architects to design, inspect and manage engineering projects within an integrated graphical user interface (GUI) on a personal computer system.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Most applications support solid modeling with boundary representation (B-Rep) and NURBS geometry, and enable the same to be published in a variety of formats.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] Based on market statistics, commercial software from Autodesk, Dassault Systèmes, Siemens PLM Software, and PTC dominate the CAD industry.
[src:construction-bim/computer-aided-design] The following is a list of major CAD applications, grouped by usage statistics.
[src:construction-bim/constructability] CII defines constructability as “the optimal use of construction knowledge and experience in planning, design, procurement, and field operations to achieve overall project objectives”.
[src:construction-bim/constructability] The term "constructability" can also define the ease and efficiency with which structures can be built.
[src:construction-bim/constructability] The more constructible a structure is, the more economical it will be.
[src:construction-bim/constructability] Constructability is in part a reflection of the quality of the design documents; that is, if the design documents are difficult to understand and interpret, the project will be difficult to build.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Practitioners of construction management are called **construction managers**.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] They combine knowledge of building science and business management to coordinate and deliver capital projects such as commercial real estate, transportation infrastructure, and military infrastructure.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Professional services firms in North America and Europe increasingly provide CM alongside related specialties such as critical path method (CPM) scheduling, delay analysis, and expert witness testimony for construction disputes.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Construction management focuses on integrating cost, schedule, quality, safety, and scope throughout the project lifecycle.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Unlike a general contractor, a CM firm or professional may be engaged as an owner’s representative to advise during feasibility, design, procurement, and construction.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] According to the Construction Management Association of America (CMAA), the seven common categories of responsibility are: Project Management Planning, Cost Management, Time Management, Quality Management, Contract Administration, Safety Management, and CM Professional Practice.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Project documentation may include diaries, logs, and daily field reports.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] These records are important for dispute resolution and can be used as evidence in legal proceedings.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Methods include mediation, minitrial, and arbitration.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Arbitration is binding and typically more costly than mediation.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] CM is taught in associate, bachelor’s, master’s, and doctoral programs.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Accreditation bodies include ABET, the American Council for Construction Education (ACCE), and the Associated Schools of Construction (ASC).
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Programs cover management, construction methods, and law.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Construction and capital project management software (CPMS) help manage budgets, schedules, documents, and collaboration.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Increasingly, cloud platforms allow owners, contractors, and consultants to work together in real time.
[src:construction-bim/construction-management] Implementing cloud-native architecture in this sector often requires specialized multi-tenant databases to seamlessly sync heavy BIM (Building Information Modeling) data across distributed remote job sites without causing operational latency.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] The **Industry Foundation Classes** (**IFC**) is a CAD data exchange data schema intended for description of architectural, building and construction industry data (ABCII).
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] The IFC file format is based on ISO 10303-21 standard and definitions of ABCII are documented by using underlying EXPRESS.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] It is a platform-neutral, open data schema specification that is not controlled by a single vendor or group of vendors.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] The IFC model specification is open and available.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] It is registered by ISO and is an official International Standard ISO 16739-1:2024.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Because of its focus on interoperability the Danish government in 2010 made the use of IFC format(s) compulsory for publicly aided building projects.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] In 2017 the Finnish state-owned facility management company Senate Properties started to demand use of IFC compatible software and BIM in all their projects.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Also the Norwegian Government, Health and Defense client organisations require use of IFC BIM in all projects as well as many municipalities, private clients, contractors and designers have integrated IFC BIM in their business.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] The popularity of the IFC data schema in construction has continued to grow, primarily for the purpose of exchanging geometry.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] The IFC initiative began in 1994, when Autodesk formed an industry consortium to advise the company on the development of a set of C++ classes that could support integrated application development.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Twelve US companies joined the consortium.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] These companies included AT&T, HOK Architects, Honeywell, Carrier, Tishman and Butler Manufacturing.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Initially named the Industry Alliance for Interoperability, the Alliance opened membership to all interested parties in September, 1995 and changed its name in 1997 to the International Alliance for Interoperability.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] The new Alliance was reconstituted as a non-profit industry-led organization, with the goal of publishing the Industry Foundation Class (IFC) as a neutral AEC product model responding to the AEC building lifecycle.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] A further name change occurred in 2005, and the IFC specification is now developed and maintained by buildingSMART.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IFC defines multiple file formats that may be used, supporting various encodings of the same underlying data.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IFC-SPF is in ASCII format which, while human-readable, suffers from common ASCII file issues, in that file-sizes are bloated, files must be read sequentially from start to finish, mid-file extraction is not possible, files are slow to parse, and definitions are non-hierarchical.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] In addition to ifcXML and ifcZIP, modern data formats include RDF/XML or Turtle (using the ifcOWL ontology), ifcJSON (JavaScript Object Notation, broadly available) and ifcHDF5 (Hierarchical Data Format v5, binary).
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] In 2020, buildingSmart had two JSON projects underway: ifcJSON v4 (a direct mapping from EXPRESS-based IFC v4) and ifcJSON v5, plus a research project experimenting with turning IFC into a binary format.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IFC defines an EXPRESS based entity-relationship model consisting of several hundred entities organized into an object-based inheritance hierarchy.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Examples of entities include building elements such as IfcWall, geometry such as IfcExtrudedAreaSolid, and basic constructs such as IfcCartesianPoint.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] At the most abstract level, IFC divides all entities into rooted and non-rooted entities.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Rooted entities derive from IfcRoot and have a concept of identity (having a GUID), along with attributes for name, description, and revision control.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Non-rooted entities do not have identity and instances only exist if referenced from a rooted instance directly or indirectly.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IfcObjectDefinition is split into object occurrences and object types.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IfcObject captures object occurrences such as a product installation having serial number and physical placement.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IfcTypeObject captures type definitions (or templates) such as a product type having a particular model number and common shape.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Occurrences and types are further subdivided into six fundamental concepts: actors ("who"), controls ("why"), groups ("what"), products ("where"), processes ("when"), and resources ("how").
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IfcRelationship captures relationships among objects.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] There are five fundamental relationship types: composition, assignment, connectivity, association, and definition.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IfcPropertyDefinition captures dynamically extensible property sets.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] A property set contains one or more properties which may be a single value (e.g. string, number, unit measurement), a bounded value (having minimum and maximum), an enumeration, a list of values, a table of values, or a data structure.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] While IFC defines several hundred property sets for specific types, custom property sets may be defined by application vendors or end users.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IfcProduct is the base class for all physical objects and is subdivided into spatial elements, physical elements, structural analysis items, and other concepts.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Products may have associated materials, shape representations, and placement in space.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Spatial elements include IfcSite, IfcBuilding, IfcBuildingStorey, and IfcSpace.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Physical building elements include IfcWall, IfcBeam, IfcDoor, IfcWindow, IfcStair, etc.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Distribution elements (HVAC, electrical, plumbing) have a concept of ports where elements may have specific connections for various services, and connected together using cables, pipes, or ducts to form a system.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Various connectivity relationships are used for building elements such as walls having openings filled by doors or windows.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Materials may be defined for products as a whole, or as layers, profiles, or constituents for specified parts.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Representations may be defined for explicit 3D shape, and optionally as parametric constraints.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Each representation is identified by IfcShapeRepresentation with a well-known name.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Placement may indicate position, vertical angle, and horizontal angle.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Quantities may be defined for take-off purposes such as Gross Area, Gross Volume, Gross Weight, Net Weight, etc.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IFC defines various quantities specific to each element type and the method of calculation according to geometry and relationships.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IfcProcess is the base class for processes and is subdivided into tasks, events, and procedures.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Processes may have durations and be scheduled to occur at specific time periods.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Processes may be sequenced such that a successor task may start after a predecessor task finishes, following the critical path method.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Processes may be nested into sub-processes for summary roll-up.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Processes may be assigned to products indicating the output produced by the work performed.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IfcResource is the base class for resources and is subdivided into materials, labor, equipment, subcontracts, crews, and more.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Resources may have various costs and calendars of availability.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Resources may be nested into sub-resources for granular allocation.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Resources may be assigned to processes indicating tasks performed on behalf of a resource.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] IfcProject encapsulates an overall project and indicates the project name, description, default units, currency, coordinate system, and other contextual information.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] A valid IFC file must always include exactly one IfcProject instance, from which all other objects relate directly or indirectly.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] A project may include multiple buildings, multiple participants, and/or multiple phases according to the particular use.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] In addition to project-specific information, an IfcProject may also reference external projects from which shared definitions may be imported such as product types.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Each external project is encapsulated using IfcProjectLibrary [IFC2x4] along with IfcRelAssociatesLibrary and IfcLibraryInformation to identify the particular revision of the imported project library.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Projects support revision control where any IfcRoot-based entity has a unique identifier and may be marked as added, modified, deleted, or having no change.
[src:construction-bim/industry-foundation-classes] Such capability allows multiple IFC files to be merged deterministically, ensuring data integrity without human intervention.
